Integration tests pinning `serve::chain_for`/`serve::render` freshness-marker behavior against an in-memory `Env`, covering the three states an editor must not conflate: STALE (recorded hash in `hashes.json` disagrees with current source), NEVER GENERATED (source exists, no sidecar/leaf/rollup recorded yet), and the plain `(absent: …)` marker used for sparse `intent.md` — the latter must render `Assessment::Unknown`, not a freshness tag, even when the directory itself is `NeverGenerated`.

Defines `FakeEnv`, a `BTreeMap<String, Vec<u8>>`-backed `Env` impl where directories are inferred from `"{path}/"` key prefixes (mirroring the real crate's `is_dir`), not declared explicitly. `sidecar(child, hash)` builds a minimal `hashes.json` body with a single `"f:{hash}"` child entry — the `f:` prefix and JSON shape must match what `ctx-context`'s hashtree/sidecar parser expects, or tests silently fail to exercise staleness. Freshness for a fresh leaf is verified via `hex_hash` from `ctx_core::hashtree` applied to the literal source bytes, so any change to that hashing scheme requires updating expected hashes here too.

`node()` is a local test helper returning `Option<&ServedNode>` (deliberately not unwrapping so failures show via `.expect` at the call site with a readable message). Tests assert both the structured `ServedNode::freshness` field and the rendered text output (`serve::render`), so a bug that affects only rendering (e.g. wrong marker string) or only classification would each be caught independently.